#+TITLE: Emacs Configuration (Literate)
#+AUTHOR: TLGS

* Customize File
Keep Customize from polluting this file by redirecting it to =custom.el=.

#+begin_src emacs-lisp
;; dont pollute this file with cutomize
(setq custom-file (expand-file-name "custom.el" user-emacs-directory))
(when (file-exists-p custom-file)
  (load custom-file))
#+end_src

* Package Management
Configure =package.el= and bootstrap =use-package=.

#+begin_src emacs-lisp

(require 'package)


(global-set-key (kbd "<escape>") 'keyboard-escape-quit)

(setq package-archives '(("melpa" . "https://melpa.org/packages/")
			 ("org" . "https://orgmode.org/elpa")
			 ("elpa" . "https://elpa.gnu.org/packages/")))

(package-initialize)
(unless package-archive-contents
  (package-refresh-contents))

(unless (package-installed-p 'use-package)
  (package-install 'use-package))

(require 'use-package)
(setq use-package-always-ensure t)
#+end_src

* Programming Support

** C mode

Have RET create newline and indent.
#+begin_src emacs-lisp
  (add-hook 'c-mode-common-hook (lambda ()
                                  (setq c-basic-offset 4)
                                  (setq c-default-style "linux") ; or "bsd", "k&r", etc.
                                  ))
#+end_src

** LSP
*** LSP Mode

Language Server Protocol client for Emacs. Provides IDE-like features:
- Go-to-definition (`M-.`)
- Find references
- Hover docs
- Code actions / refactoring
- Symbol rename
- Completions via company/capf
- Per-language intelligence via external LSP servers

This setup loads `lsp-mode` lazily and activates LSP in common programming modes
using `lsp-deferred` to avoid blocking startup.

#+begin_src emacs-lisp
  (use-package lsp-mode
    :commands (lsp lsp-deferred)
    :init
    ;; Prefix for lsp-command-map (C-c l ...)
    (setq lsp-keymap-prefix "C-c l")

    ;; Performance / UX settings
    (setq lsp-enable-symbol-highlighting t
          lsp-enable-snippet t
          lsp-prefer-flymake nil) ;; prefer flycheck if present

    :hook ((c-mode          . lsp-deferred)
           (c++-mode        . lsp-deferred)
           (python-mode     . lsp-deferred)
           (rust-mode       . lsp-deferred)
           (go-mode         . lsp-deferred)
           (js-mode         . lsp-deferred)
           (js-ts-mode      . lsp-deferred)
           (typescript-mode . lsp-deferred)
           (tsx-ts-mode     . lsp-deferred)
           (lua-mode        . lsp-deferred)
           (sh-mode         . lsp-deferred)))

  ;; UI extras (hover docs, sideline info)
  (use-package lsp-ui
    :after lsp-mode
    :commands lsp-ui-mode)

  ;; Company for completions (via capf)
  (use-package company
    :config
    (global-company-mode 1))
  
  (with-eval-after-load 'company
    (add-to-list 'company-backends 'company-capf))
#+end_src

Allow C-h to fallthrough to emacs when company is active
#+begin_src emacs-lisp
(with-eval-after-load 'company
  ;; Don't let company grab C-h while the popup is active
  (define-key company-active-map (kbd "C-h") nil)
  ;; Optional: also free up F1 as help
  (define-key company-active-map (kbd "<f1>") nil))
#+end_src

Make company use C-<return> complete selection so TAB and RET always enter new text.
#+begin_src emacs-lisp
  (with-eval-after-load 'company
    ;; Enter = newline
    (define-key company-active-map (kbd "<return>") nil)
    (define-key company-active-map (kbd "RET") nil)
    (define-key company-active-map (kbd "C-m") nil)

    ;; Explicit completion keys
    (define-key company-active-map (kbd "C-<return>") #'company-complete-selection))
#+end_src

*** Language Servers (Installation)
The following language servers are used by =lsp-mode= hooks above.
Install them with your system package manager.

**** C / C++ — clangd
- Server: =clangd=
- Used for: =c-mode=, =c++-mode=

#+begin_src shell
# Homebrew (recommended)
brew install llvm

# Optionally add to PATH if needed:
# echo 'export PATH="/opt/homebrew/opt/llvm/bin:$PATH"' >> ~/.zshrc
# clangd --version
#+end_src

**** Python — pyright
- Server: =pyright=
- Used for: =python-mode=

#+begin_src shell
# Node-based (original)
npm install -g pyright

# Or Python wrapper variant:
# pip install pyright
#+end_src

**** Rust — rust-analyzer
- Server: =rust-analyzer=
- Used for: =rust-mode=

#+begin_src shell
# Homebrew
brew install rust-analyzer

# Or via rustup:
# rustup component add rust-analyzer
#+end_src

**** Go — gopls
- Server: =gopls=
- Used for: =go-mode=

#+begin_src shell
# Go toolchain required
go install golang.org/x/tools/gopls@latest
#+end_src

**** JavaScript / TypeScript — tsserver
- Server: =tsserver= (via =typescript= package)
- Used for: =js-mode=, =js-ts-mode=, =typescript-mode=, =tsx-ts-mode=

#+begin_src shell
npm install -g typescript typescript-language-server
#+end_src

**** Lua — lua-language-server
- Server: =lua-language-server=
- Used for: =lua-mode=

#+begin_src shell
# Homebrew
brew install lua-language-server
#+end_src

**** Shell / Bash — bash-language-server
- Server: =bash-language-server=
- Used for: =sh-mode=, =bash-mode=

#+begin_src shell
npm install -g bash-language-server
#+end_src

**** Verifying LSP Setup
After installing servers:

1. Open a file in the relevant mode (e.g. =.c=, =.py=, =.rs=).
2. Ensure =lsp-mode= starts (look for “LSP” in the modeline).
3. Test:
   - =M-.= → go to definition
   - =M-?= → find references
   - =C-c l= → LSP command map
*** LSP Debugging
Useful tools and workflows when an LSP server is not starting or not behaving as expected.

**** Check LSP Logs
Shows communication between Emacs and the language server.

#+begin_src emacs-list :tangle no
;; Open the main LSP log buffer
(lsp-workspace-show-log)
#+end_src

Or interactively:

- =M-x lsp-describe-session=
- =M-x lsp-workspace-show-log=

These buffers often reveal missing executables, crashed servers, or invalid workspace roots.

**** Restart the LSP Server
Sometimes the server needs a clean restart after config or dependency changes.

#+begin_src emacs-list :tangle no
(lsp-workspace-restart)
#+end_src

Interactive:

- =M-x lsp-workspace-restart=
- =C-c l r= (if using lsp-command-map)

**** Verify the Server Executable
If the server isn’t starting, confirm it's on PATH. Examples:

#+begin_src shell
which clangd
which pyright
which rust-analyzer
which gopls
#+end_src

If Emacs was launched from GUI (macOS), PATH may differ from shell PATH.  
Solution: initialize PATH inside Emacs:

#+begin_src emacs-list :tangle no
(use-package exec-path-from-shell
  :config
  (exec-path-from-shell-initialize))
#+end_src

**** Check the Project Root Detection
LSP uses project “root markers” (e.g., =compile_commands.json=, =pyproject.toml=, =go.mod=, =Cargo.toml=).

If detection fails, override manually:

#+begin_src emacs-list :tangle no
;; Force a directory as LSP project root
(setq lsp-client-packages '(lsp-clients))
#+end_src

Use:

- =M-x lsp-workspace-folders-add=
- =M-x lsp-workspace-folders-remove=

**** Common Diagnoses

- **Server installed but not found** → PATH issue  
- **Server exits immediately** → missing dependency, invalid config file  
- **Definition jumps don't work** → incomplete project root  
- **Hover/docs not showing** → missing capabilities in server or disabled in lsp-ui  
- **High CPU** → disable semantic tokens or code lenses  

#+begin_src emacs-list :tangle no
(setq lsp-semantic-tokens-enable nil)
(setq lsp-lens-enable nil)
#+end_src

**** Check Capabilities
Useful to see what features the server supports:

- =M-x lsp-capabilities=

**** Enable Verbose LSP Logs (for deep debugging)
#+begin_src emacs-list :tangle no
(setq lsp-log-io t)
#+end_src

This logs every message sent/received.  
Turn it off afterward; it gets noisy.

**** Final Step: Clean Workspace
Sometimes leftover metadata causes odd behavior.

- =M-x lsp-workspace-restart=
- or delete =.lsp-session-v1= file in =~/.emacs.d/=
  
* Org Mode and Markdown
Org core configuration, directory layout, logging behavior, and export defaults.

