* Version Control
** Magit
Magit is an interactive, porcelain-style Git interface for Emacs.  
Key features:
- Status buffer (`magit-status`) as the main entry point  
- Stage/unstage hunks or lines  
- Commit, amend, reword, squash, fixup  
- Browse logs, branches, remotes, stashes  
- Interactive rebase UI  
- Resolve merge conflicts in-buffer  
- Push/pull with popups guiding available actions  
- Transient-based menus allow discoverability (`?` always shows help)

Key bindings (once Magit loads):
- =C-x g= → `magit-status` for the current project  
- =s= / =u= → stage / unstage  
- =c c= → commit  
- =P u= → push to upstream  
- =F u= → pull from upstream  
- =b b= → switch branches  
- =l l= → log view  
- =TAB= → expand a section  
- =RET= → act on thing at point  

Configuration below adds Magit, enables autosaving before commits, and improves commit message editing.

#+begin_src emacs-lisp
(use-package magit
  :commands (magit-status magit-blame)
  :bind (("C-x g" . magit-status))
  :config
  ;; Save buffers automatically when invoking Magit commands
  (setq magit-save-repository-buffers 'dontask)

  ;; Use the full frame for commit messages (optional)
  (setq git-commit-fill-column 72
        git-commit-summary-max-length 50)

  ;; Show word-level diffs by default
  (setq magit-diff-refine-hunk 'all))
#+end_src

** Magit Notes
- Magit creates a “status buffer” representing repository state, not a shell interface.  
- Everything is interactive: press ? on any popup to see available actions.  
- Magit uses Transient menus: press key prefixes, then subcommands (e.g. =c c=).  
- Rebase workflows are guided via `magit-rebase`; Magit validates operations before executing them.  
- The “diff → stage → commit → push” loop mirrors Git’s conceptual model but exposes more structure.  
- Magit automatically detects project roots (via Git repos) and uses them as context for all actions.

* DAP Debugging (GUI-style debuggers)

Use `dap-mode` + `dap-ui` as a generic, VS Code–style debugger front-end.
This gives you:

- Breakpoints in the fringe
- Locals / call stack / sessions buffers
- Watch / expressions buffer
- Integrated debug REPL
- Hover tooltips for values (when LSP supports it)

Breakpoints:
dap-breakpoint-toggle
dap-breakpoint-delete-all
dap-breakpoint-condition
  
dap-breakpoint-hit-condition

dap-breakpoint-log-message

** Core dap-mode configuration

#+begin_src emacs-lisp
  (use-package dap-mode
    :after lsp-mode
    :commands (dap-debug dap-debug-edit-template)
    :init
    ;; Let dap auto-wire UI pieces for common workflows.
    (setq dap-auto-configure-features
          '(sessions locals controls tooltip))
    :config
    ;; Turn on the global modes that make it feel "GUI-ish".
    (dap-auto-configure-mode 1)
    (dap-ui-mode 1)
    (dap-tooltip-mode 1)
    (tooltip-mode 1)
    (dap-ui-controls-mode 1))
#+end_src

Notes:

- `dap-debug` starts a debug session from a registered template.
- `dap-debug-edit-template` lets you interactively edit / create templates, then
  you `M-x eval-buffer` to persist them in your config.
- Most “GUI stuff” lives in dedicated dap-ui buffers (locals, stack, etc.)
  
** Language adapters

The Debug Adapter Protocol needs per-language “adapters” that talk to your
runtime or underlying debugger. Below are the ones I’m using for Rust, Go,
C/C++, Python, and JS/TS.

*** Rust + C/C++ (LLDB / GDB via cpptools or codelldb)

For native code, use either Microsoft’s cpptools adapter or codelldb.
You can have both enabled; pick per-project via templates.

#+begin_src emacs-lisp
  ;; C/C++/Rust via VS Code C++ tools (cpptools).
  (use-package dap-cpptools
    :ensure nil
    :after dap-mode
    :config
    ;; One-time helper to download the VS Code C++ extension and set up the
    ;; debug adapter. You can comment this out after the first run if you want.
    (dap-cpptools-setup))
#+end_src

If you prefer codelldb:

#+begin_src emacs-lisp :tangle no
  ;; Alternative: C/C++/Rust via codelldb.
  ;; You need to have codelldb installed somewhere on your system.
  (use-package dap-codelldb
    :after dap-mode
    :config
    ;; Example adapter config if you want to override the default path:
    ;; (setq dap-codelldb-debug-program '("/path/to/codelldb"))
    )
#+end_src

You’ll later define project-specific templates that point to your compiled
binary (e.g. `target/debug/myprog` for Rust, `build/myprog` for C/C++).

*** Go (Delve DAP)

Use Delve’s native DAP mode via `dap-dlv-go`.

Prereqs: Go toolchain + Delve (`dlv`) installed.

#+begin_src emacs-lisp
  ;; Go debugging via Delve (dlv dap).
  (use-package dap-dlv-go
    :ensure nil
    :after dap-mode)
#+end_src

Typical template will point `:program` at a package/main or binary; see
project-local examples below.

*** Python (debugpy)

Use `dap-python`, which wraps the `debugpy` adapter. You’ll want a Python 3
install and `debugpy` available in whatever environment you’re using.

#+begin_src emacs-lisp
  ;; Python debugging via debugpy.
  (use-package dap-python
    :ensure nil
    :after dap-mode
    :config
    ;; Optionally tell dap-python how to find your interpreter.
    ;; (setq dap-python-executable "python3")
    )
#+end_src

Debug templates typically specify `:program` (entry script), `:cwd`, and
optional `:args` / `:env`.

*** JavaScript / TypeScript (Node)

For Node-based debugging, use the Node adapter integration from `dap-mode`.
You’ll need Node.js and a JS debug adapter (e.g. vscode-js-debug) installed.

#+begin_src emacs-lisp
  ;; Node.js debugging (JS/TS via node adapter).
  (require 'dap-node)

  ;; You may need to customize this to point at the JS debug adapter you install.
  ;; Example (adjust paths to your system):
  ;;
  ;; (dap-register-debug-provider "node"
  ;;   (lambda (conf)
  ;;     (plist-put conf :debugServer 4711)
  ;;     conf))
  ;;
  ;; (dap-register-debug-template
  ;;  "Node::current file"
  ;;  (list :type "node"
  ;;        :request "launch"
  ;;        :name "Node::current file"
  ;;        :program "${file}"
  ;;        :cwd "${workspaceFolder}"
  ;;        :runtimeExecutable "node"))
#+end_src

For TS, you can point the adapter at either:

- compiled JS (with source maps), or
- a TS runner like `ts-node` as `:runtimeExecutable`.

** Project-local debug templates (per language)

Keep per-project DAP templates close to the code. I usually either:

- put them in a small `project-debug.el` and load it via `.dir-locals.el`, or
- keep them in a “Project-specific config” section of my Emacs.org and
  manually evaluate when I’m working in that project.

Debug Template for debugging c code on my m1 macbook pro

#+begin_src emacs-lisp :tangle no
  (require 'dap-mode)

  (defun project-dap--register ()
    "Register DAP debug templates for this project."
    (require 'dap-cpptools)

    (dap-register-debug-template
     "c debug"
     (list :type "cppdbg"
           :request "launch"
           :name "proj::cpp"
           :MIMode "lldb"
           :targetArchitecture "arm64"
           :program (expand-file-name "build/tests"
                                      (project-root (project-current)))
           :cwd (project-root (project-current))
           :stopAtEntry t)))

  (project-dap--register)
  (provide 'debug)

#+end_src

Example “skeletons” (not tangled by default):

#+begin_src emacs-lisp :tangle no
  ;; Rust: debug main binary built by `cargo build`.
  (dap-register-debug-template
   "Rust::main"
   (list :type "lldb"                    ; or "cppdbg"
         :request "launch"
         :name "Rust::main"
         :program "${workspaceFolder}/target/debug/myprog"
         :cwd "${workspaceFolder}"))

  ;; Go: debug current package / main file with Delve.
  (dap-register-debug-template
   "Go::current-file"
   (list :type "go"
         :request "launch"
         :name "Go::current-file"
         :mode "exec"
         :program "${file}"
         :cwd "${workspaceFolder}"))

  ;; C/C++: debug compiled binary via cpptools.
  (dap-register-debug-template
   "C++::Debug"
   (list :type "cppdbg"
         :request "launch"
         :name "C++::Debug"
         :MIMode "gdb"                   ; or "lldb"
         :program "${workspaceFolder}/build/myprog"
         :cwd "${workspaceFolder}"
         :stopAtEntry :json-false))

  ;; Python: debug a main script.
  (dap-register-debug-template
   "Python::main"
   (list :type "python"
         :request "launch"
         :name "Python::main"
         :program "${workspaceFolder}/main.py"
         :cwd "${workspaceFolder}"
         :justMyCode :json-false))

  ;; Node: debug current JS file.
  (dap-register-debug-template
   "Node::file"
   (list :type "node"
         :request "launch"
         :name "Node::file"
         :program "${file}"
         :cwd "${workspaceFolder}"
         :runtimeExecutable "node"))
#+end_src

Workflow:

1. Make sure language server + adapter prereqs are installed for the project.
2. Evaluate the relevant template forms (or the whole buffer).
3. Run `M-x dap-debug` and select one of your named templates.
4. Use the dap-ui buffers (sessions, locals, stack, expressions) as your
   “GUI debugger” while stepping through code.
